    10	# Python Interface
    11	
    12	This file owns Python-visible symbol spelling and attribute casing.
    13	Cross-binding parity remains owned by `design/bindings.md`.
    14	
    15	## Runtime surface
    16	
    17	The canonical runtime verbs available to Python callers are:
    18	
    19	- `Engine.open(...)`
    20	- `engine.write(...)`
    21	- `engine.search(...)`
    22	- `engine.close()`
    23	- `admin.configure(...)`
    24	
    25	`Engine.open(...)` returns the engine handle plus the structured open report
    26	owned by `design/engine.md`.
    27	
    28	> **0.6.0 caveat (2026-05-17, Phase 12-TX).** The PyO3 binding currently
    29	> returns the engine handle only; the structured open report is dropped.
    30	> Native Rust `Engine::open` returns `OpenedEngine { engine, report:
    31	OpenReport }` and the report is populated, but binding-side surfacing
    32	> defers to 0.6.1 (slice 12-TX-OPENREPORT). Clients that need
    33	> migration-version-reached / embedder-identity-confirmed / open-stage
    34	> data wait for 0.6.1.
    35	
    36	`Engine.open(path, *, config=None, **engine_config)` accepts the
    37	engine-owned knobs from `design/engine.md` in snake_case:
    38	
    39	- `embedder_pool_size`
    40	- `scheduler_runtime_threads`
    41	- `provenance_row_cap`
    42	- `embedder_call_timeout_ms`
    43	- `slow_threshold_ms`
    44	
    45	The keyword form and `EngineConfig` object form are equivalent. Python
    46	executor usage remains caller-owned and is not an engine config field.
    47	
    48	## Engine-attached instrumentation / control
    49	
    50	These are public instance methods, not extra top-level SDK verbs:
    51	
    52	- `engine.drain(timeout_s=...)`
    53	- `engine.counters()`
    54	- `engine.set_profiling(enabled=...)`
    55	- `engine.set_slow_threshold_ms(value=...)`
    56	
    57	Subscriber attachment is provided by:
    58	
    59	- `engine.attach_logging_subscriber(logger, *, heartbeat_interval_ms=None)`
    60	
    61	The helper maps engine events into Python `logging.LogRecord`s with the stable
    62	`fathomdb` payload described by `design/bindings.md`.
    63	
    64	## Caller-visible data shapes
    65	
    66	- `WriteReceipt.cursor`
    67	- `SearchResult.projection_cursor`
    68	- `SearchResult.soft_fallback.branch`
    69	
    70	`soft_fallback.branch` uses the typed values owned by `design/retrieval.md`.
    71	
    72	## Errors
    73	
    74	Python exposes one catch-all base class plus one concrete subclass per canonical
    75	row in `design/errors.md`.
    76	
    77	Examples of caller-visible subclasses:
    78	
    79	- `DatabaseLockedError`
    80	- `CorruptionError`
    81	- `MigrationError`
    82	- `IncompatibleSchemaVersionError`
    83	- `EmbedderIdentityMismatchError`
    84	- `EmbedderDimensionMismatchError`
    85	- `SchemaValidationError`
    86	- `OverloadedError`
    87	- `ClosingError`
    88	
    89	Payload fields remain typed attributes; callers do not dispatch on message
    90	text.
    91	
    92	## Non-presence
    93	
    94	Python does not expose recovery verbs or doctor-only flags. In particular,
    95	there is no SDK equivalent of `recover`, `check-integrity`, `--quick`,
    96	`--full`, or `--round-trip`. See `design/recovery.md`.

