     8	---
     9	
    10	# ADR-0.6.0 — No shims / no deprecation policy
    11	
    12	**Status:** accepted (HITL 2026-04-27, decision-recording).
    13	
    14	Promoted from critic-3 M-2. The "0.6.0 has no compat path with 0.5.x"
    15	posture is in `dev/notes/0.6.0-rewrite-proposal.md` but is not yet an
    16	ADR. Cross-cuts every other Phase 1 ADR; needs a single citable
    17	artifact so the policy is not re-litigated under release pressure.
    18	
    19	## Context
    20	
    21	0.5.x carried deprecation shims to keep API compat across releases.
    22	Concrete example from commit `b4fe850` (0.5.6):
    23	
    24	```python
    25	admin.configure_vec(embedder)  # legacy 0.4.x form
    26	# routed through admin.configure_embedding (modern form)
    27	# synthesized a VecProfile-shaped return value from the embedder identity
    28	```
    29	
    30	That shim regressed in 0.5.6 because rename-passes shipped without
    31	shim-specific tests. Memory `feedback_release_verification` codified
    32	"deprecation shims are first-class code paths with their own tests."
    33	
    34	The 0.6.0 rewrite is a clean break (per existing non-goals: no data
    35	migration, no upgrade path for 0.5.x users in 0.6.0). The same
    36	posture applies to API: no 0.5.x→0.6.0 shims at all.
    37	
    38	## Decision
    39	
    40	### Across-major (0.5.x → 0.6.0): zero shims
    41	
    42	- 0.6.0 ships **no** deprecation shims for 0.5.x APIs.
    43	- No `legacy_*` modules. No `compat_v0_5` features. No
    44	  `#[allow(deprecated)]` in crate roots.
    45	- No "raw_sql escape hatch for migration" (would also violate
    46	  ADR-0.6.0-typed-write-boundary).
    47	- No re-routing of old verbs through new ones (e.g. no
    48	  `configure_vec(embedder)` → `configure_embedding` adapter).
    49	- 0.5.x clients cannot import 0.6.0; 0.6.0 clients cannot run against
    50	  0.5.x DBs (already fresh-DB-only).
    51	
    52	### Within 0.6.x (0.6.0 → 0.6.x patch / minor)
    53	
    54	- Patch releases (0.6.0 → 0.6.1): no API breaks. Bugfix-only.
    55	- Minor breaks within 0.6.x are discouraged. When they happen, change
    56	  is announced + removed in the **same release**. No multi-release
    57	  deprecation cycles. No "soft-removal then hard-removal" pattern.
    58	
    59	### Across-major (0.6 → 0.7+): out of scope
    60	
    61	- Future major-version transitions are decided in their own ADRs.
    62	- This ADR does **not** prejudge 0.7's posture.
    63	
    64	## Options considered
    65	
    66	**A — Zero shims at major boundary; no within-major deprecation
    67	cycles (chosen).** Pros: cleanest possible boundary; matches
    68	already-decided non-goals (no data migration, no upgrade path);
    69	removes the "speculative knobs / silent feature-gated fallbacks"
    70	Stop-doing class at the source. Cons: 0.5.x users have no migration
    71	helper. Acceptable per existing non-goal.
    72	
    73	**B — Allow shims under feature flag `legacy_v0_5`.** Pros: gentler
    74	break for 0.5.x users. Cons: re-introduces the exact pattern
    75	0.5.6 hit (untested shim, regression); feature-flag fallbacks are
    76	the Stop-doing class; expectation creep ("just one more shim, one
    77	more release"); doubles test surface for the 0.6.0 lifetime.
    78	
    79	**C — Provide a 0.5.x → 0.6.0 migration tool, not shims.** Pros:
    80	no in-engine compat code; a separate binary that reads 0.5.x state
    81	and emits 0.6.0 inputs. Cons: still requires reading 0.5.x schema
    82	(the rewrite proposal explicitly drops this); duplicates the
    83	"no data migration" non-goal in tool form. Rejected.
    84	
    85	## Consequences
    86	
    87	- Every other ADR may cite this ADR when refusing a "but can we add
    88	  a shim for $client?" request.
    89	- ADR-0.6.0-typed-write-boundary cannot be softened by
    90	  `legacy_sql_compat` flag (cross-cite).
    91	- ADR-0.6.0-default-embedder cannot have a `python_st_compat` flag
    92	  (cross-cite).
    93	- ADR-0.6.0-operator-config-json-only cannot accept `.toml` "for one
    94	  more release" (cross-cite).
    95	- `release-policy.md` updated: changelog discipline includes the
    96	  "announced + removed in same release" rule for within-0.6.x
    97	  breaks.
    98	- Followup `release-checklist.md`: add a release-gate question
    99	  ("does this release introduce any deprecation? if yes, refuse").
   100	- Memex / OpenClaw integration narratives (already dropped per
   101	  Phase 1a disposition) cannot re-emerge as "wire-compat shim
   102	  because $client uses 0.5.x"; cite this ADR.
   103	
   104	## Non-consequences (what this ADR does NOT do)
   105	
   106	- Does not forbid internal renames during 0.6.0 pre-freeze drafting.
   107	- Does not decide wire-format versioning (separate decision-index #15).
   108	- Does not decide 0.7+ posture.
   109	- Does not prohibit deletion of unused fields / methods within a
   110	  release (deletions are encouraged per net-negative-LoC Keep-doing).
   111	
   112	## Citations
   113	
   114	- HITL decision 2026-04-27.
   115	- `dev/notes/0.6.0-rewrite-proposal.md` § "What we got wrong" #5;
   116	  § "Architectural invariants".
   117	- `b4fe850` (0.5.6 atexit + legacy `configure_vec` shim regression).
   118	- Memory `feedback_release_verification` (deprecation shims as
   119	  first-class code paths).
   120	- Stop-doing entries: speculative knobs / silent feature-gated
   121	  fallbacks; defect deferral patterns.

