     7	status: accepted
     8	---
     9	
    10	# ADR-0.6.0 — Embedder protocol
    11	
    12	**Status:** accepted (HITL 2026-04-27).
    13	
    14	This ADR records the language-agnostic contract for any `Embedder` impl
    15	plugged into FathomDB. It exists because critic-3 (ASYNC-3) showed
    16	that the user-supplied embedder is the deadlock vector for both Python
    17	(GIL re-entrancy via `pyo3-log`) and TS (napi callback storms). The
    18	protocol is sync, isolated, contractually pure, and language-agnostic.
    19	
    20	## Context
    21	
    22	Default embedder = candle (per ADR-0.6.0-default-embedder.md). Users
    23	may also supply their own embedder in any binding language (Rust,
    24	Python, TS). The engine dispatches embedder calls from a dedicated
    25	engine-owned thread pool (Invariant B from ADR-0.6.0-async-surface.md).
    26	Within that dispatch, the engine has zero control over what the
    27	user's impl does. The protocol below pins what user impls must
    28	contract to do (and not do).
    29	
    30	## Decision
    31	
    32	### Trait shape (Rust canonical form)
    33	
    34	```rust
    35	pub trait Embedder: Send + Sync {
    36	    /// Identity of the embedding model. NEVER carried by vector configs;
    37	    /// per memory project_vector_identity_invariant.
    38	    fn identity(&self) -> EmbedderIdentity;
    39	
    40	    /// Embed a single text. Returns a unit-norm `Vec<f32>` of dimension
    41	    /// `self.identity().dimension`.
    42	    ///
    43	    /// Contract:
    44	    ///   - Pure function: no callbacks into the engine.
    45	    ///   - No logging emission via pyo3-log / tracing-subscriber inside
    46	    ///     this call (Python impls especially).
    47	    ///   - Sync return; impl may use async internally (e.g.
    48	    ///     `asyncio.run(self._async_embed(text))`) but engine sees sync.
    49	    ///   - Output L2-norm must be 1.0 ± 1e-5; engine asserts in debug
    50	    ///     builds.
    51	    ///   - Output length must equal `identity().dimension`.
    52	    fn embed(&self, text: &str) -> Result<Vec<f32>, EmbedderError>;
    53	}
    54	```
    55	
    56	Bindings adapt this trait to language-native shapes:
    57	
    58	- **Python**: `class Embedder: def identity(self) -> EmbedderIdentity; def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]`. PyO3 bridge converts.
    59	- **TypeScript**: `interface Embedder { identity(): EmbedderIdentity; embed(text: string): number[] }`. napi-rs bridge converts.
    60	
    61	### Five mandatory invariants
    62	
    63	**Invariant 1 — Unit-norm output.** Every vector returned by `embed()`
    64	has L2-norm 1.0 ± 1e-5. Engine asserts in debug builds on every call;
    65	release builds document. Required for sqlite-vec cosine semantics.
    66	
    67	**Invariant 2 — Pure function: no engine callbacks.** Inside `embed()`,
    68	the impl must not call back into any FathomDB engine method. No
    69	`engine.write(...)`, no `engine.search(...)`, no `engine.query(...)`.
    70	Violation = re-entrancy deadlock (ASYNC-2 class). Documentation +
    71	binding-side runtime check (debug builds): per-call thread-local
    72	`engine_in_call` flag; `embed()` body that triggers an engine call
    73	panics in debug.
    74	
    75	**Invariant 3 — No logging emission from inside `embed()` (Python).**
    76	Python `Embedder.embed` impls must not emit logs via
    77	`logging.getLogger(...).info/...` or any path that `pyo3-log` bridges
    78	back to the Rust `log` crate, while the call is in-flight. Reason:
    79	`pyo3-log` re-acquires the GIL while the engine-owned thread already
    80	holds it for the embedder call → exact GIL deadlock class
    81	(`dev/archive/pyo3-log-gil-deadlock-evidence.md`). Test fixture:
    82	asserting embedder + `logging.basicConfig(level=DEBUG)` does not hang
    83	on N=4 concurrent writes.
    84	
    85	**Invariant 4 — Engine-owned thread.** Embedder dispatch is on a
    86	dedicated thread pool owned by the engine, sized `num_cpus::get()`,
    87	configurable per engine via `Engine.open(... embedder_pool_size: N)`.
    88	Asyncio worker threads, libuv blocking pool, V8 main thread, JS
    89	worker_threads — none ever run an embedder call directly. Enforced by
    90	the bindings layer.
    91	
    92	The pool-size override exists because embedded deployments vary
    93	substantially: some colocate FathomDB with latency-sensitive app code
    94	and need to cap embedder concurrency to preserve host responsiveness,
    95	while others run bulkier local models and need to raise or lower
    96	parallelism to match actual CPU / memory pressure. This is an
    97	operator-facing throughput-vs-contention control, not a binding-only
    98	escape hatch.
    99	
   100	**Invariant 5 — Per-call timeout.** Every `embed()` call is wrapped in
   101	a timeout (default 30s; configurable). Timeout fails the call with
   102	`EmbedderError::Timeout`; does not corrupt writer state; cancels by
   103	allowing the embedder thread to finish + discard, never by aborting
   104	mid-call (no thread-cancel API in standard pthreads / Tokio joinhandle
   105	abort is best-effort).
   106	
   107	## Options considered
   108	
   109	**A — Sync trait with five invariants (chosen).** Pros: smallest
   110	contract surface; deadlock vectors closed by structural rules + tests;
   111	language-agnostic. Cons: Python/TS users with naturally-async
   112	embedders pay an `asyncio.run` / `await` cost per call; documented.
   113	
   114	**B — Async trait with `async fn embed(&self, text: &str)`.** Pros:
   115	matches modern Rust / Python / TS idiom for I/O-bound embedders. Cons:
   116	forces tokio in the engine surface (which Option A of
   117	ADR-0.6.0-async-surface.md explicitly rejected); doubles every binding's
   118	adapter; reopens GIL-vs-runtime questions. Rejected.
   119	
   120	**C — Two traits (sync + async, user picks).** Pros: flexibility. Cons:
   121	"two shapes for one verb" — same Stop-doing pattern as 0.5.x's
   122	`configure_vec(kind_or_embedder)`. Doubles tests, docs, dispatch
   123	paths. Rejected.
   124	
   125	**D — Thread-isolated impl (Python sub-interpreter per PEP 684).**
   126	Pros: real GIL isolation across embedder calls. Cons: requires CPython
   127	3.12+; ecosystem not ready (most pyo3 / numpy / torch don't yet
   128	support sub-interpreters). Premature; revisit in 0.7+.
   129	
   130	## Consequences
   131	
   132	- `interfaces/rust.md`: documents the canonical `Embedder` trait.
   133	- `interfaces/python.md`: documents the Python `Embedder` ABC,
   134	  Invariants 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 spelled out with examples; explicit warning
   135	  about `logging.basicConfig + pyo3-log` interaction.
   136	- `interfaces/typescript.md`: documents the TS `Embedder` interface
   137	  (sync at engine boundary; impl may use async internally via
   138	  top-level `await` inside the engine-owned thread); cancellation TBD
   139	  (followup).
   140	- `design/embedder.md`: documents the dispatch layer (engine-owned
   141	  thread pool, per-call timeout impl, debug-build assertions).
   142	- Test plan items:
   143	  - Python embedder + `logging.basicConfig(level=DEBUG)` + 4
   144	    concurrent writes does not hang (regression test for the 0.5.x
   145	    `pyo3-log-gil-deadlock-evidence` class).
   146	  - Embedder returning non-unit-norm vector triggers debug-build
   147	    assertion (and a typed error in release).
   148	  - Embedder calling back into engine triggers debug-build re-entrancy
   149	    panic.
   150	  - Embedder timeout (mock embedder sleeping > 30s) returns typed
   151	    `EmbedderError::Timeout`; does not corrupt subsequent writes.
   152	- Stop-doing: enforces "embedder owns identity" (Invariant in
   153	  `dev/notes/project-vector-identity-invariant.md`); embedders never
   154	  carry identity strings on vector configs.
   155	
   156	## Citations
   157	
   158	- HITL decision 2026-04-27 (Path 2 + Path 1 invariants from
   159	  ADR-0.6.0-async-surface.md).
   160	- Critic-3 ASYNC-3 (GIL re-entrancy class) + EMB-2 (L2-norm enforcement)
   161	  - EMB-4 (engine-owned thread) + EMB-1 (mean-pool decision).
   162	- Memory `project_vector_identity_invariant`.
   163	- Memory pattern from `dev/archive/pyo3-log-gil-deadlock-evidence.md`,
   164	  commits `cf0b190`, `d09deb4`.

