     8	---
     9	
    10	# ADR-0.6.0 — Text-query latency gates
    11	
    12	**Status:** accepted (HITL 2026-04-27, decision-recording — promoted from
    13	FU-REQ-010-TEXT-LATENCY).
    14	
    15	Phase 3a-promoted acceptance ADR. Parallel to
    16	ADR-0.6.0-retrieval-latency-gates; closes REQ-010 with an authoritative
    17	numerical anchor.
    18	
    19	## Context
    20	
    21	Phase 3a critic [REQ-010] flagged that the harvested
    22	`production-acceptance-bar.md` value of `p95 ≤ 150 ms` for text query had
    23	no accepted ADR backing, no workload definition, no scale, and no
    24	percentile model parallel to the vector retrieval ADR. Requirements lock
    25	blocked on a real text-query latency anchor.
    26	
    27	Two paths to resolution were available:
    28	
    29	1. Promote to its own ADR mirroring `ADR-0.6.0-retrieval-latency-gates`.
    30	2. Fold under canonical-read freshness (REQ-013) with a generous
    31	   acceptance.md bound.
    32	
    33	Path 1 chosen. Text query is a load-bearing user surface (REQ-053 lists
    34	`search` among the five-verb application API; FTS5 is the engine
    35	underneath text mode). It deserves the same gate-and-fixture treatment
    36	vector retrieval gets, not a hand-waved acceptance bound.
    37	
    38	## Decision
    39	
    40	- **p50 ≤ 20 ms; p99 ≤ 150 ms.** (p99 set at 150 ms rather than 100 ms
    41	  to absorb shared-runner scheduler jitter on tier-1 CI; tighten to
    42	  100 ms when a measured baseline justifies it — followup
    43	  `FU-TXT-LAT-TIGHTEN`.)
    44	- **Scope:** text-only query mode (FTS5 path). If `search` (REQ-053)
    45	  auto-routes to hybrid (text + vector) by default, the hybrid path
    46	  inherits ADR-0.6.0-retrieval-latency-gates' embedder-bearing gate,
    47	  not this one.
    48	- **Workload definition:**
    49	  - **Dataset:** 1,000,000 chunk rows. Synthetic-English-like text
    50	    with a Zipfian token-frequency distribution; vocabulary size and
    51	    text-generator parameters specified by `test-plan.md` fixture
    52	    (the same fixture row-set that backs
    53	    ADR-0.6.0-retrieval-latency-gates' chunk table — only the
    54	    secondary indexes differ: this ADR exercises the FTS5 index;
    55	    retrieval ADR exercises the `vec0` index).
    56	  - **Mean chunk text:** ≈ 500 bytes.
    57	  - **Query mix:** single-token MATCH and one phrase MATCH; query
    58	    tokens drawn from the **50th–90th percentile term-frequency
    59	    band** (avoids both stop-word degenerate slow paths and rare-token
    60	    trivial-fast paths).
    61	  - **Concurrency:** **QPS = 1** (sequential, one in-flight query at
    62	    a time), single-process, **no concurrent writes**.
    63	  - **Cache state:** warm. Warmup protocol = run the full query suite
    64	    once and discard; measure on the second pass. Matches whatever
    65	    `test-plan.md` codifies for the retrieval-latency-gates fixture.
    66	  - **Sample count:** ≥ 1,000 measured queries per percentile
    67	    calculation.
    68	  - **Tokenizer:** whatever FTS5 tokenizer ships as default per
    69	    `design/retrieval.md`. Gate re-validated if the default tokenizer
    70	    changes.
    71	- **Latency boundary:** **in-process** client call → result list.
    72	  Includes safe-grammar parse (per REQ-034) + FTS5 MATCH + canonical
    73	  row fetch + result serialization to in-process result type. Excludes
    74	  IPC / network / subprocess-bridge envelope, graph-expand,
    75	  and FTS5 `snippet()` / `highlight()` extraction.
    76	
    77	Numbers tighter than the vector ADR because text query has no embedder
    78	in the path: no model load, no inference, no GPU/CPU embedding cost.
    79	FTS5 + canonical row fetch is index lookup + B-tree fetch.
    80	
    81	## Options considered
    82	
    83	**A — p50 ≤ 20 ms; p99 ≤ 150 ms (chosen).** FTS5 + canonical fetch is
    84	expected to be well under p50 ≤ 20 ms on warm cache; p99 set with
    85	shared-runner scheduler jitter headroom. Matches "text faster than
    86	vector" intuition (no embedder); testable. (Original draft proposed
    87	p99 ≤ 100 ms; relaxed per critic [high-1] pending measured baseline.)
    88	
    89	**B — p50 ≤ 50 ms; p99 ≤ 200 ms** (mirror retrieval-latency-gates).
    90	Trivial to hit; abdicates the "text is cheaper than vector" property
    91	that should fall out of architecture; loose enough to mask FTS5
    92	regressions.
    93	
    94	**C — p50 ≤ 10 ms; p99 ≤ 50 ms.** Aggressive; requires careful FTS5
    95	tokenizer tuning + heavy mmap; risks failing CI on slower runners; no
    96	forcing function justifies it.
    97	
    98	**D — p95 ≤ 150 ms** (the harvested value). p95 is the wrong percentile
    99	for an interactive read path (tail latency matters more than median);
   100	no scale / workload defined; rejected for the same reasons critic
   101	[REQ-010] rejected the harvest.
   102	
   103	**E — Fold under REQ-013 (canonical-read freshness) with generous
   104	acceptance bound.** Conflates two distinct user concerns (freshness =
   105	"how stale" vs latency = "how slow"). Loses the tier-1 perf-gate
   106	discipline. Rejected.
   107	
   108	## Consequences
   109	
   110	- `requirements.md` REQ-010 updated to restate this ADR's numbers; ADR
   111	  is authoritative.
   112	- `test-plan.md`: perf AC with seeded fixture per the workload
   113	  definition above; p50/p99 reported per CI run; fails build on
   114	  regression. Fixture row-set shared with retrieval-latency-gates
   115	  fixture (same 1M chunk-row table); only the secondary index under
   116	  test differs (FTS5 here, `vec0` in the retrieval ADR).
   117	- `design/retrieval.md`: documents FTS5 tokenizer choice (default + any
   118	  alternatives), token-frequency-band fixture generator, and required
   119	  SQLite PRAGMAs that achieve A. Tokenizer choice itself is owned by
   120	  `design/retrieval.md` (or its own ADR), not by this latency ADR.
   121	- CI perf job runs on the same pinned tier-1 runner shape as
   122	  retrieval-latency-gates (`x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu` per
   123	  ADR-0.6.0-tier1-ci-platforms reference target).
   124	- Concurrent-write impact on text-query latency is a separate followup
   125	  (parallel to retrieval-latency-gates' equivalent followup); not gated
   126	  here.
   127	- Graph-expand adds its own latency; ADR sets the **default-pipeline**
   128	  gate. Stage-augmented latency is documented but not gated in 0.6.0.
   129	- FU-REQ-010-TEXT-LATENCY closed by this ADR.
   130	
   131	## Citations
   132	
   133	- HITL 2026-04-27.
   134	- ADR-0.6.0-retrieval-latency-gates (parallel structure).
   135	- ADR-0.6.0-tier1-ci-platforms (reference target).
   136	- REQ-010, REQ-034, REQ-053 (cross-cited).
   137	- Phase 3a critic [REQ-010] (forcing function).

